segments.text: What kind of work ethic did Aggies have?
Were they lazy or energetic?
In terms of building a bonfire?
I think we didn't
disregard our responsibilities.
I mean, if you don't keep your grades up, the upperclassmen are on your back, and you had to post your grades on the door.
And if you flunk a course, you're going to hear about it.
But you also, we didn't have a good system like we have now, but you get some help sometimes.
They'd say, Mr. So-and-so wants you to come down to his room.
And we'd say, now, what's going on in your history class, or whatever it was?
And they'd try to help us and things like that.
When you arrived, who was the commandant?
Bull Boatner.
Describe him.
He was like a bull.
I had no personal relationships with him.
About what size was he?
About your build, I'd say.
Five-nine?
Maybe, I don't think he's any bigger than that, but like I said, I never, you know, I never trigon trotted.
Why did y'all call him Bull?
That was his nickname.
He was a bull.
That's what they're calling the trigon bulls.
And, uh, and Guy Malloy after him.
M, how, how does spell Malloy?
M-E-L-L-O-Y.
L-O-Y.
And describe him.
Well, he was a tall, slender type guy, and, uh, uh, he's, uh,
very business-like.
You didn't see much of them, though, at my level again, because, you know, they're taking care of the bin and the tri-gun, whatever.
I didn't see them in the Quad very much at all.
And, of course, I knew his career quite a bit after that, because his son was one of my students when I was an instructor at the command zone of South College down at Lloyd Junior.
And Bill Boatner, of course, everybody knew about him in Korea.
and when he took over Cogedo Prison.
Now, he was not an Aggie, was he, Boatner?
No, neither one of them.
That's what I thought.
I had General Boatner back down here one time when he was a viewing officer, and he wasn't, I mean, he was nice, but he didn't seem overjoyed.
Describe as much as you can that Corps revolt and march on
President Gilchrist's house.

Well, of course, we knew that this thing was stirring, that they were going to move the fish out to Brownfield, and so I think it emanated from the Houston area that this is not going to happen, and it got organized that we're going to not put up with this, and we want the Corps to stand behind.
These are former students that were running this thing, I think.
And so one night at midnight, whistles blew and horns blow and everything, and we fall out, and we're marching on the President's House.
I was a junior there.
And we fall out, and the Bulls come, and the band was out there with the instruments, and the Bulls told the band they were not going to use those instruments.
They were going to the United States Army, which they did.
And so they grounded those and went back and got their own.
A lot of them had their own drums or whatever.
So we marched in formation over there, and not everybody in the Corps went.
And there was some speech making by some seniors, which I couldn't hear, but I knew what was going on.
And the seniors were pulling their diamonds off.
I'm a junior, I got stripes, and stupidly, I give them my stripes.
Never did get them back.
But, you know, it's kind of all of the leader stuff that wasn't smart enough to know you don't do.
And did President Gilchrist come out on the porch and hear?
But I don't know what, were there shames there, but probably ordered us back to the dorm.
We then did not, no more formations.
We did go to class, we did wear the uniform, we saluted the officers, and the rest of the life was as usual.
A bunch of the guys were going out across the state making speeches.
Again, I didn't know much about that.
We didn't like it, you know, because they were all our fish.
So it never worked.
It didn't work very well, I don't think.
And the heart of the argument was putting the freshmen out at Bryan Field.
Right.
And the purpose of that was to try to avoid hazing.
Right, try to stop the hazing.
It still went on that scenario.
I'm sure it's one of them.
People went out to Bryan Field to haze them.
I didn't, but I do know of people that did.
And I did go out there on occasion.
They'd use some of the guys, the doors would go out and conduct drills or something like that.
And I did that a few times.
But we just said there was no way I'd work with them four years later.
And they wrote that in three or four years.
And when they put them back in as sophomores, the sophomores essentially were doing what the freshmen were doing, cleaning rooms.
Now, when all of the brass and the stripes were handed to President Gilchrist, he accepted them, didn't he?
He sure did.
He didn't give them back.
I guess some people did.
You had to go full board.
So it was an unsuccessful... Well, yeah, I think that it was a dumb thing, of course, as you look back on it.
I don't think it cost me anything in terms of going in the military because my grades were not
sufficiently high to be a distinguished student.
So when I went in, I went in as a reserve officer rather than a regular, and there was no prejudice involved in my records that I knew of.
But there might have been on some of the others?
Could have been, yes.
During your four years here, were there any sad events here?
There were no fires,
No tragedies here on campus, were there?
I don't remember any.
And the Korean War starts after you graduate, so okay.
I was already in there.
So nothing like we had last week where you remember where you were when you heard the news.
Do you remember going to Silver Taps for the first time?
I remember going to it, but we already knew what you were supposed to do and so forth, and it was a pretty sobering event.
Did everybody respect Silbertaps?
Oh, sure.
I mean, this third place was blacked out.
You wouldn't dare wish for nothing.
If you did, you'd pay a price for it.
We were very serious about that.
Do you remember going to Muster as a student?
According to where?
Muster, as a student.
I went to, they had Muster up in front of the administration building, and I went to it up there.
Was there an out-of-town speaker to Muster then?
I don't remember.
Usually just somebody from the campus, a football coach.
And it was usually held early in the evening, wasn't it?
Yes.
on the steps of the admin building.
What about yell practice?
Yeah, plenty of those up in Goodwin Hall Tuesdays and Thursdays, I think.
And then was there a midnight yell practice?
Yes.
Where was it held?
It was held in various places, but I don't think we went to Kyle Field for them more than once or twice.
And was the Grove?
The Grove was operating and showing movies.
In fact, that's where some of the old practices were.
Let's see.
Bonfire.
Was there a bonfire your freshman year?
Just a pile of trash.
And where'd y'all get it?
just went around and got old stuff from the iron grocery store and wood.
We didn't take people's outhouses and things like that.
About how long did y'all work on Bonfire?
I don't think more than a week or two.
It wasn't really a significant event.
How did it change, bonfire, in your four student years?
By the time you were a senior, were there using logs?
A few, but nothing.
There wasn't any transportation and chainsaws.
I mean, people didn't have trucks and things like that, pickups.
So it was about like a high school bonfire now.
And it really wasn't that, to me it was not as significant an event as it was later when I came back.
And it was held on the Driffin.
Let's see, the, what was there at Northgate in your student days?
Well, there was a drug store up there, and Pollock, and Zubik to Taylor, and of course
Lupo.
Lupo, a barber shop.
I think there was one gift shop on the jewelry store on the corner.
And I think it was right in the movie, I don't remember.
There was one eating place there, I think.
And then at South Gate was the pharmacy, the drug store.
Oh, okay.
And the railroad station was busy, wasn't it?
Oh, yes.
The college station.
Right.
Where was the bus stop?
Where'd you catch them?
I'd catch them off the gate.
Not by the post I was pulling down, but I don't remember what was there.
I know I used to meet my girlfriend from 2U there once in a while.
And was the Aggieland Inn still going?
About how many...
I never was in it.
It didn't have many rooms, I know.
Is that right?
And when did the MSC construction begin?
Do you remember?
It wasn't while I was a student.
It wasn't finished when you were a student?
No.
It's after that?
No.
Okay.
I was about out.
I don't remember.
And so the only place within walking distance of the campus where an out-of-town guest could spend the night.
The dormitories.
was in the dormitories or at the Aggieland Inn.
Well, there was a motel over at the North Gate, I mean the East Gate.
Yeah, yeah, but that would be a long walk.
Or there were some that, you know, the profs boarded some of the doors, but usually they dumped out of dormitories.
As you and your buddies looked at the campus leaders, what was the most respected campus leadership position?
Oh, we didn't look up to the Corps commander by any means.
He was too far away from us.
But that was the most glamorous student leadership role, wasn't it?
Oh, yeah, but the company commander was the one that was the most influence on us.
As far as you all knew, how was the Corps commander selected?
I had no idea.
I figured, well, for one thing, they had to be on the contract.
I know that for sure because I'm the guy that changed the commander not having a contract because I remembered I didn't have a contract and I felt like I was as good as any other.
But the Army, the military was wrong about that, I still think they were wrong.
As far as you knew, how was the outfit
the company commander selected?
How was he run?
How was he selected?
He was first sergeant.
He didn't move up.
But how did he become a first sergeant?
I presume that the class selected and the sophomores select who in their group they want to be the first sergeant.
That's the way it was when I was in the company of the battering.
And what did you and your buddies think about yell leaders?
Well, we didn't think them bad of them.
We thought they were pretty big wheels.
It's a pretty, pretty big job.
One of the guys really liked to have the day, too.
And what about the band?
Well, we loved the band, but we didn't love them as a unit.
My senior year, my battery was on the bottom floor of the band dorm, and we didn't have a lovely fire with the band.
They were on two, three, and four, and they didn't want us in that dorm.
Were the band, were they noisy?
Were they what?
Were they noisy?
Oh, yeah, sure.
They were bothersome to you guys?
Yeah, you bet.
They harass us.
Were there any pranks back and forth?
Not particularly.
We didn't, once in a while somebody's room would get drowned out, but I think that was a personal type thing.
It only happened to me one time while we were gone.
My roommate was first sergeant, and he was pretty
tough on them.
And we came back and everything we owned was in the floor, and flooded out.
And, you know, I didn't do anything, but I didn't, you know, after it set me back big in Rwanda, believe me, they don't think about that.
Did you and your buddies know about steam tunnels when you were a student?
No.
Did you ever go down in them?
Yeah.
How far did you?
Just far enough to get down there and know I didn't want to be down there and got out.
As far as you know, from whatever source, how far in that era, how far could somebody have gone in a steam tunnel?
I'm told you could get as far as the library.
Is that right?
But I don't know that for a fact.
I do know a couple of guys that were tunnel rats, you know, and that was what they were known as in the course.
I don't know what they did down there.
And wasn't there a way supposedly to turn off the water and turn on the water?
Well, see, there was supposedly a secret organization going around at the time, the T's or something like that.
The T.T.'s?
T.T.
's, and I don't know whether they were involved with that or not.
I didn't, I knew that there was something like that, but that's all I knew.
Because I know old Bob, we used to work for Colas before I died there.
Anyway, he was trying to track it down, but I don't think he ever found it.
Were you aware of any other, did you ever hear of any other secret fraternity here?
The Stickers?
The Swastikers?
Now, during your student days, these veterans came back and there were big, big veterans housing all over.
How did A&M change during
your sophomore, junior, senior year with all those veterans and those young brides and their kids?
I really don't think that there was any animosity or anything.
I think most Aggies were proud of all these guys that, you know, did what they did.
And I think most of them are proud that some of these guys will never be able to see a college.
Reckon it, reckon the grades went up?
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, you had to, there's no question, competition
I know I worked harder because you could pretty much come by before the vets came by.
And the project houses were still down there.
They were still in use.
Now, you gradually changed your major.
When did you zero in on ag education?
No, I was on just straight education.
Oh, education.
That was my junior year.
And you had gotten advice from Dr. Harrington.
Who else gave you advice?
I really didn't have any close contact with anybody after Dr. Harrington.
And when did you go to summer camp?
summer of, uh, 48.
After your... Well, see, I didn't have a contract until after my junior year.
I had to have a contract.
So, uh, I was behind my classmates.
I went with the class behind me.
And where did you go to summer camp?
Fort Sells.
What was it like?
Well, you know, it was dark soup compared to being at it.
We had
We had Aggie companies and OU had Oklahoma companies and we competed with each other and got along great.
And of course we liked it because everybody there was in the artillery business and so forth, but Fort Sells had a good program back then.
Did, in hindsight, did that experience help to make the active duty service more attractive to you?

I tell you, if there wasn't anything they could have done, it wouldn't have helped them, because I was very, very motivated towards it, and also because of some family members that were in the service during the war.
The patriotism was pretty high.
Let's see.
We were talking a while ago about drinking and so forth.
What about smoking?
What did Aggies smoke in those days?
Well, a lot of them did.
Cigarettes.
What brands?
I don't know.
I never smoked, and so I don't know.
Do you have a guess as to how many Aggies smoked?
Percentage?
Half?
Did they smoke in the dormitories?
Was it legal for them to smoke in their room?
As far as I know, it was not in their rooms.
And did Aggie smoke cigars except at games?
No, I think it was strictly a Yale practice type thing.
What about pipes?
Rare.
Chewing tobacco?
Not like today.
Snuff?
Nothing.
They probably went on in like the Cavs outfits and so forth.
They didn't go in the artillery outfits.
I don't know what the difference is.
Did you and your buddies even know the words
marijuana or heroin?
I had no interest in drugs.
Yeah, I thought those were non-existent.
Let's see, and you said you went, you didn't go to downtown Bryan very often.
No.
I went on the trolley car when I did.
Do you remember what it cost?
Ten cents.
Ten cents.
And caught it at Northgate?
at the North Gate and got off in downtown Brown.
There was a restaurant down there where people used to go and eat, kind of a cafeteria type place.
And it ran about how often?
I think it was about every 30 minutes, but I don't know.
I didn't, like I said, I didn't eat it very often.
And you picked up your mail at North Gate?
At George's, I think.
There was a mailbox down there about where the trigon is.
Oh, okay.
a little cafeteria type thing over there.
See, we did silver tabs, muster, yell practice.
How much did your senior ring cost?
Do you remember?
I think it was just about the same thing as the monthly pay of the contract, $28, $29.
And how did you feel when you put that ring on the first time?
Like I feel today.
I'm thinking of getting me another one.
This is my second one.
Do you have any good ring stories where somebody recognized it somewhere on the other side of the world or you lost it and it came back or anything like that?
No, except that I'm always looking at somebody's hand and particularly
I go to Barksdale a good bit, and Aggies are all over the place up there, and I belong to that club up there too.
So you make friends, and you see them, and it don't take but a minute to be telling lies together.
But I don't know anybody that had her brain recovered.
I read these stories in Aggie and so forth.
My only ring story is the one in the Cal display over there was Judy's ring that died.
And that was my first ring.
And Ed was in, you know, pregnant assistant.
Ed Cooper.
Ed Cooper was working on some project over there on former students, and I was talking about
you know, getting her a ring, and she wanted a big one.
And I said, Ed, you know, would Balfour do anything with this old ring of mine?
He said, I don't know, but I found out.
Well, he took my original ring and cut this crest off and put her class year on there.
And that's my original ring with her class year on it.
Oh, hell no.
In that case.
And Balfour said they won't do any more like that.
So that is an original.
So the ring you're wearing now is your second.
Second ring.
And because I was really proud of Judy, and she had never had a chance to go to school.
And your boots, where'd you buy those?
Hollock.
You remember what they cost?
I'm sorry?
How much did they cost?
Where'd you get that?
Saved up for it.
You had saved up from your, and how did you feel when you put those on?
You know, just like putting it around.
And where are they now?
I sold them to a guy that was in the band named T.A.
Carlton, and I don't know where he is now, but I sold them for 70 bucks.
And we didn't wear our boots like they do now.
We only wore them on special occasions.
Now they wear them all the time.
And so was your first time to wear them publicly at Final Review your junior year?
And did anyone in your family come for that?
My mother and daddy.
And how did you feel, and how did they feel?
They were proud.
And was there any distinguished visitor that day, any famous?
I don't remember any.
We just didn't, I don't remember a whole lot of them, you know, with the reviewing stand or anything like that.
Most of the time going to a choral review wasn't much fun.
Now, let's see.
During your days, didn't Patton or Eisenhower come to visit once or twice?
Not that I recall.
They might have.
Then when you were a senior, describe final review and commencement.
Well, first of all, my class did not have a commencement.
We graduated the real beginning, the ones that began.
Some of them graduated in
ahead of time, but the main part of the class graduated in January of 49, and we voted not to have a ceremony.
We had a commissioning ceremony in Dine Hall, and that was it.
We didn't want it really, but because it was a hassle, we wanted to get our commissioning and get on the way.
So we didn't have a commission.
So you graduated in January of 49?
January 19.
And went on active duty?
First of March.
First of March.
As you look back on it, what is it that creates this special Aggie spirit?
Why are Aggies so proud?
I think it's maybe because we're having an interest in each other, and we're sticking together, and that's just kind of bred into you when you're a fish.
And if you don't stick together, you'll never make it.
So, you know, even today, fish buddies will sell you fish buddies.
Are there some events that encourage that sticking together?
I don't think any more than the living in the dormitory lifestyle.
But do silver taps and muster and yelp?
I think, you know, the guys that are RVs probably have, they're melded, and the guys are in the cowlower, and that sort of thing.
You know, they have a loyalty to the outfit, but also have that to the activity.
Fish-grilling people, for example, are very tight, and that was my mistake on that.
And I should have never let the Marines have that.
I'm not putting the Marines down, but they have a different attitude.
No, I don't know.
That never occurred to me.
The whole Aggies didn't feel like I felt.
I know my brother doesn't feel as strong as I do.
He does now, but he didn't now.
Looking back on it, what did you learn at A&M that has been important to you in your life?
Well, I think a lot of things I've already learned.
I don't lie to anybody.
I don't steal.
I wouldn't think of it.
And I can't tolerate drug uses and such as that.
And I went through a lot of it with my own kids.
And I think just standing by each other is really what I learned about the Corps, that these are the guys you can count on.
And through the years, how has that helped you?
How has this A&M experience helped you?
Well, it certainly opened a lot of doors in the Army, and just like the west runners, you know, they help each other.
You see an Aggie, and he assumes that you're
you're going to be a good officer and you can count on him.
And I don't know that you can differentiate between him and some other officer, but the others may have to prove themselves.
That Aggie's already proved himself.
I didn't ever seek any employment or, you know, being an Aggie got me a job out there because I never worked in a civilian market.
If, make believe that we have just hired you to be the consultant
to A&M's leaders, and you're to advise A&M's leaders about what they should do in the future for this school.
What advice would you give A&M's leaders today?
Well, for one thing, I don't think I'd tell them we've got to cut the, we can't continue to grow that everything.
I think it's getting to the point that I don't enjoy coming back like I used to.
I mean, I'm just talking short years ago.
But the kids are still the best kids in the world.
But I think that they get more rambunctious than they used to be.
I think a lot of things go on, and I don't know how the administration can control that.
this off-campus type lifestyle, just living together and so forth.
It's tough.
It goes under dormitories, too.
And I thought it like hell when I was coming out, but I knew we was going to have trouble with it.
And there was a fair amount of it that I had to take action on.
So I don't know.
Academically,
Goodness knows they're doing the one thing I always hoped to do at a medical college.
And I think we're very strong in the arts.
I used to be an engineer, and to me, I'm not artistic in any manner, but my leaning has always been in that direction.
And I'm glad to see it, and I'm proud of the College of Education.
And I get sometimes weary of coming back to the campus, because if you don't bring your checkbook with you sometimes, you know, sometimes they overdo that.
